            <creation>This story, with the short title "A Woman Whose Dog Ate Her Dinars," is recent: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around <date>1800</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>A young woman named Mary had a leather pouch containing twenty dinars’ worth of silver and gold. One day, after dining with her father, she dropped the pouch on the ground, and the family dog ate it. When she realized it was missing, she looked everywhere, but she couldn’t find it. So, she went to church and prayed for her namesake, the Virgin Mary, to return the pouch to her. Sometime later, the young woman’s mother dreamt that the Virgin Mary came to her and promised that the pouch would be found in due course. Around this same time, the dog that had eaten the pouch vomited it up in an out-of-the way place. Four months later, when she went out to clean up dog poop in the yard, the young woman found her pouch, miraculously intact and untouched.</p>
            </abstract>
